The cool thing: a true relationship algebra

Normal algebra treats the world like this:

a = b

But a meaning-aware system would treat the world more like this:

\mathcal{R}(a,b,c,\dots)

where the primitive object is not a number, but a relation bundle.

Step 1: make relations first-class objects

Instead of writing:

A = B

you write:

r := (A \xrightarrow{\text{causes}} B)

or

r := (A \overset{\text{depends-on}}{\longrightarrow} B)

Now relations themselves can be manipulated.

Step 2: define operators on relations

You can combine relations the way algebra combines numbers.

Let:
	•	⊕ = relation merge
	•	∘ = composition
	•	⊗ = contextual binding
	•	~ = analogy / structural similarity
	•	⇒ = causal implication
	•	↔ = reciprocal coupling
	•	⊣ = constraint imposed by
	•	⊢ = supports / entails

Then you can write things like:

(A \xrightarrow{gives} B) \;\otimes\; (B \xrightarrow{needs} C)

and compose them into:

A \xrightarrow{\text{provisions-through}} C

That is already more like thought than ordinary algebra.

Step 3: make multi-way relations native

A lot of meaning is irreducibly multi-part.

“John gave Mary a book yesterday” is not really four separate statements. It is one event:

Give(John, Mary, Book, Yesterday)

So the atomic unit becomes something like:

\rho = \langle \text{type}, e_1, e_2, \dots, e_n; w,c,t \rangle

where:
	•	type = relation kind
	•	e_i = entities
	•	w = weight / strength
	•	c = confidence
	•	t = time

Now memory is not just symbols. It is weighted relational events.

Step 4: define “equation” as balance across a relation field

Instead of equality, define coherence:

\Phi(\text{left structure}) \equiv \Phi(\text{right structure})

Meaning two things do not have to be symbolically equal. They can be structurally equivalent.

Example:

\text{Battery} \xrightarrow{powers} \text{Motor}

is not equal to

\text{Food} \xrightarrow{powers} \text{Body}

but under a mapping they may satisfy:

(\text{Battery} \xrightarrow{powers} \text{Motor}) \sim (\text{Food} \xrightarrow{powers} \text{Body})

That ~ is not equality. It is analogy-preserving structure.

That is the cool thing: you get a system where metaphor, logic, causality, memory, and math all live in one symbolic layer.

A tiny starter notation

Here’s a compact prototype.

Atomic relation

\[
[A \;{\buildrel op \over \to}\; B]_{w,c,t}
\]

Example:

\[
[\text{Rain} \;{\buildrel causes \over \to}\; \text{WetGround}]_{0.9,0.95,t_0}
\]

Hyperrelation

\langle op : A, B, C, D \rangle

Example:

\langle Give : John, Mary, Book, Tuesday \rangle

Composition

[A \to B] \circ [B \to C] = [A \to C]

Merge

r_1 \oplus r_2 = \text{combined relation field}

Constraint

r \;\bot\; s

means the two relations conflict.

Resonance / analogy

r_1 \sim r_2

means they preserve the same relational pattern under translation.

So instead of equations, you get something like relagrams or thought circuits.

